post_text: Superintendent Dr. George Rafferty will provide additional guidance to our staff and families regarding the governor's extension in a communication this afternoon.
shared_text:
Governor Phil Murphy
April 16 at 1:20 PM ·

BREAKING: Our public schools will remain closed through at least Friday, May 15th.

We need to be guided by where the facts on the ground, science, and public health take us. That means it will not be safe to reopen our schools for at least another four weeks.

I’ve made this decision in careful consultation with New Jersey Department of Health and New Jersey Department Of Education, among other key stakeholders.

I know this is hard. But we are saving lives and we must maintain the course.

post_text:
March 13, 5:45 p.m.

A Message from Superintendent Dr. George J. Rafferty:
Dear Parents and Staff:

I have just completed a series of conference calls with county school and health officials. Pursuant to those calls, all Burlington County Schools have been directed by the Burlington County Health Department to close to students from Monday, March 16 through Thursday, April 9. Remote education will be provided during this time.

Schools are scheduled to reopen on April 20, following our Spring break. This 30-day closure is intended to mitigate the spread of the COVID-19 virus.

All Mount Laurel School Staff are scheduled to report to schools from 8 a.m. to 3 p.m. on Monday and Tuesday, March 16 and 17 to prepare for the delivery of online instruction.

I will provide you with additional information via School Messenger regarding the details of our plans moving forward.

I appreciate your patience and understanding during this trying time. Please understand that the health and safety of our students is our primary concern.

post_text: Mount Laurel Canine Department Officers Chris O'Prandy and Kyle Gardner and their canine partners trained along with a Gloucester Township Officer and canine and two canine specialists today in our school bus lot. The dogs are being familiarized with every possible environment they may have to enter for search and detection purposes. Within the next three months, Mount Laurel will have canines specifically trained in evidence recovery, search and rescue, narcotics and bomb detection. Very impressive!

post_text: Thursday, September 5 is the first day of school in Mount Laurel! This is a full-day of school for all K-8-grade students. Lunch will be served in our cafeterias. All bus-riders should have received a letter with their bus number, pick-up location and pick-up time. Class assignments have been sent to PowerSchool accounts. Supply lists are on our website. Countryside and Fleetwood Schools start at 8:30 a.m. and dismiss at 2:55 p.m. Hillside, Larchmont, Parkway and Springville start at 9 a.m. and dismiss at 3:25 p.m. Hartford School's day starts at 8 a.m. and ends at 2:35 p.m. Harrington Middle School opens at 7:30 a.m. and the day ends at 2:05 p.m. We are excited to welcome our school family!

post_text:
Good morning, Parents and Staff Members:

Please be aware that Mount Laurel is experiencing some major roadway issues this morning due to flooding. Most significant are the closures of portions of Ramblewood Parkway and Hartford Road.

Parkway School can be accessed from Route 73, but not from the Church Road side.

Springville School can be accessed from the Elbow Lane side, but not from the Hainesport Road side.

Please be patient as we reroute buses around these and other roads with flooded areas this morning. Expect busing delays.

Please drive carefully. We will update you if necessary as roads are cleared by police.

T E Harrington Middle
June 1, 2019 at 5:25 PM ·

Okay, so you know our SeaPerch Team is competing at the University of Maryland this weekend? Well, they ROCKED the pool today! Just look at some of the course details on the SeaPerch website to get a feel for the obstacles they had to overcome. Then, get this: they timed 29 seconds on the obstacles and 3:16 on the mission, earning the maximum points for doing it all under four minutes! THAT is science at work. Tomorrow, they present their engineering details notebook at noon. Rooting for OUR TEAM! We'll keep you posted.
https://www.seaperch.org/course

post_text: Students in Harrington's Challenge-Based Leaning Classes studied local and world issues and the charities that help those causes this year. Today, they presented the charities' missions, gave suggestions for future growth and partnered with GivingCycle.org to make donations to their causes. The winning non-profits were: People for the Poor,Table to Table, Education Works, NJ Conservation Foundation, Surfrider Foundation, Conserve Wildlife Foundation for New Jersey. More than $3,200 was donated to the charities by GivingCycle.

Ocean County Prosecutor's Office
April 11, 2019 at 3:29 PM ·

Less than a week ago the Ocean County Prosecutor’s Office High Tech Crimes Unit arrested a convicted sex offender that was posing as an 11 year old girl on social media. Ocean County Prosecutor Bradley D. Billhimer is warning all parents about the dangers of these social media platforms and apps. Parents must be vigilant in monitoring their children’s online activity. It is imperative to know what your children are sharing, looking at and who they are communicating with.
#weareallinthistogether #ocpo

T E Harrington Middle
November 6, 2018 at 11:58 AM ·

Yesterday's Mock Election results for US House and Senate seats in New Jersey are in. With all Harrington students given the opportunity to vote after having researched the candidates in Social Studies classes, the results are: Andy Kim (D) 70% to Tom McArthur (R) 30% for the House seat. In the Senate race, Bob Hugin (R) won by only one vote against Bob Menendez (D) 50.056% to 49.944%.

T E Harrington Middle
November 6, 2018 at 11:58 AM ·

Yesterday's Mock Election results for US House and Senate seats in New Jersey are in. With all Harrington students given the opportunity to vote after having researched the candidates in Social Studies classes, the results are: Andy Kim (D) 70% to Tom McArthur (R) 30% for the House seat. In the Senate race, Bob Hugin (R) won by only one vote against Bob Menendez (D) 50.056% to 49.944%.

post_text:
Today's Unofficial Vote Count during the Special School Election was 2,552 for and 646 against! The Referendum has passed!

On behalf of the Board of Education and Administration, I would like to offer our sincere appreciation for the interest and enthusiasm shown by so many within the Mount Laurel community for the referendum plan put before the voters on October 2 to improve our schools. Its approval by voters will allow us to responsibly upgrade our facilities and expand programs to benefit Mount Laurel's children into the future.

Thank you, Parents and Staff, for your tireless support!

On behalf of the Board of Education and Administration, I would like to offer our sincere appreciation for the interest and enthusiasm shown by so many within the Mount Laurel community for the referendum plan put before the voters on October 2 to improve our schools. Its approval by voters will allow us to responsibly upgrade our facilities and expand programs to benefit Mount Laurel's children into the future.

Thank you, Parents and Staff, for your tireless support!

post_text: The clock is ticking ...Polls open until 8 p.m. on this very important question for our schools.
text: The clock is ticking ...Polls open until 8 p.m. on this very important question for our schools.

post_text:
Dear Mount Laurel School Family:

As you know, our Special School Election will be held Tuesday, October 2 from noon to 8 p.m. All polling places will be open for your convenience (list linked below). This is simple and easy; there is only one question on the ballot and it is about your schools.

A successful referendum will result in a reduction of approximately $50 on your annual school taxes for the average assessed home.

It will also allow us to:

Receive $12,498,720 in state-aid towards the total project that is available now
Upgrade our aging facility infrastructure in all schools
Implement full-day kindergarten in September, 2019
Realize energy savings of $194,000 each year
Please be there on Tuesday. Your vote matters.

Sincerely,

George J. Rafferty

T E Harrington Middle
December 20, 2017 at 3:25 PM ·

Parents, have you checked your child's phone lately? Sometimes the littlest things can have an impact on how your child is perceived by others. Yesterday, a Mount Laurel Mom shared a screen shot of her child's phone open to the app House Party on the Mount Laurel Community Facebook Page. (So important to share such concerns.) It's apparently an app that allows users to chat online live, all at the same time. She said she reviewed the app and it seemed fine, but then she noticed that some of the students who were on the app had selected very inappropriate user names. Please remind your child that even the selection of a user name should be considered carefully. If it would make a friend's parents frown, it probably should not be used.

Please remind your child that even the selection of a user name should be considered carefully. If it would make a friend's parents frown, it probably should not be used.
text: Parents, have you checked your child's phone lately? Sometimes the littlest things can have an impact on how your child is perceived by others. Yesterday, a Mount Laurel Mom shared a screen shot of her child's phone open to the app House Party on the Mount Laurel Community Facebook Page. (So important to share such concerns.) It's apparently an app that allows users to chat online live, all at the same time. She said she reviewed the app and it seemed fine, but then she noticed that some of the students who were on the app had selected very inappropriate user names. Please remind your child that even the selection of a user name should be considered carefully. If it would make a friend's parents frown, it probably should not be used.
